## APOE Gene Risk & Family History Implications

### Genetic Risk Assessment
- **APOE ε4 allele** is the strongest common genetic risk factor for late-onset Alzheimer's disease
- **Risk multipliers:** One copy ≈4-fold risk; two copies ≈12-fold risk (in European ancestry populations)
- **Gene frequency:** ~20% of world population carries APOE ε4
- **Critical interaction:** Family history of dementia is only significantly associated with increased AD risk **among APOE ε4 carriers** — suggests genetic-environmental interaction (other factors must be active with the genetic predisposition)
- **For this 38F:** Unknown APOE status, but family history + young age makes genetic testing worthwhile before starting interventions

**Actionable:** Recommend APOE genotyping via direct-to-consumer or clinical test (~$100-150) to stratify intervention intensity

